# Safety and validation rules

- Fail closed on non-finite values, invalid frames, invalid joint names, unknown units, stale state, or unevaluated required safety metrics.
- Validate the interpolated terminal trajectory waypoint-by-waypoint using FK.
- At minimum validate lateral line error, TCP approach-axis error, monotonic target progress, terminal pose error, joint limits, and available collision clearance.
- Report the first offending waypoint and all applicable failure categories.
- Do not silently clamp target vectors, joint states, quaternions, planner outputs, or validation metrics.
- Any future residual correction is bounded and processed by deterministic `SafetyProjector` logic outside the learned policy.
- The initial residual implementation is zero output. Do not add an RL package without a later specification.
- Never let residual logic disable collision checking, modify collision geometry, change joint limits, or choose a global joint configuration.
- Tests must include negative cases that deliberately violate each critical constraint.
- GPU integration tests must be marked separately from lightweight unit tests.
- Every randomized test and benchmark must record a seed and enough input data for exact replay.
- Do not claim physical-robot accuracy from simulation-only thresholds or results.
